[src:apache-samza/apache-kafka] Kafka was originally developed at LinkedIn, and was subsequently open sourced in early 2011.
[src:apache-samza/apache-kafka] Jay Kreps, Neha Narkhede and Jun Rao helped co-create Kafka.
[src:apache-samza/apache-kafka] Graduation from the Apache Incubator occurred on 23 October 2012.
[src:apache-samza/apache-kafka] Jay Kreps chose to name the software after the author Franz Kafka because it is "a system optimized for writing", and he liked Kafka's work.
[src:apache-samza/apache-kafka] Apache Kafka is a distributed log-based messaging system that guarantees ordering within individual partitions rather than across the entire topic.
[src:apache-samza/apache-kafka] Unlike queue-based systems, Kafka retains messages in a durable, append-only log, allowing multiple consumers to read at different offsets.
[src:apache-samza/apache-kafka] Kafka uses manual offset management, giving consumers control over retries and failure handling.
[src:apache-samza/apache-kafka] If a consumer fails to process a message, it can delay committing the offset, preventing further progress in that partition while other partitions remain unaffected.
[src:apache-samza/apache-kafka] This partition-based design enables fault isolation and parallel processing while allowing ordering to be maintained within partitions, depending on consumer handling.
[src:apache-samza/apache-kafka] In 2025, Apache Kafka introduced "Queues for Kafka", adding share groups as an alternative to consumer groups.
[src:apache-samza/apache-kafka] This feature enables queue-like semantics where consumers can cooperatively process records from the same partitions, with individual message acknowledgment and delivery tracking.
[src:apache-samza/apache-kafka] Unlike traditional consumer groups where partitions are exclusively assigned, share groups allow the number of consumers to exceed partition count, making it ideal for work-queue patterns while maintaining Kafka's durability and scalability benefits.
[src:apache-samza/apache-kafka] This development addresses the common challenge of "over-partitioning" that many Kafka users face.
[src:apache-samza/apache-kafka] Kafka Connect (or Connect API) is a framework to import/export data from/to other systems.
[src:apache-samza/apache-kafka] It was added in the Kafka 0.9.0.0 release and uses the Producer and Consumer API internally.
[src:apache-samza/apache-kafka] The Connect framework itself executes so-called "connectors" that implement the actual logic to read/write data from other systems.
[src:apache-samza/apache-kafka] Kafka Streams (or Streams API) is a stream-processing library written in Java.
[src:apache-samza/apache-kafka] It was added in the Kafka 0.10.0.0 release.
[src:apache-samza/apache-kafka] The library allows for the development of stateful stream-processing applications that are scalable, elastic, and fully fault-tolerant.
[src:apache-samza/apache-kafka] The main API is a stream-processing domain-specific language (DSL) that offers high-level operators like filter, map, grouping, windowing, aggregation, joins, and the notion of tables.
[src:apache-samza/apache-kafka] Additionally, the Processor API can be used to implement custom operators for a more low-level development approach.
[src:apache-samza/apache-kafka] The DSL and Processor API can be mixed, too.
[src:apache-samza/apache-kafka] For stateful stream processing, Kafka Streams uses RocksDB to maintain local operator state.
[src:apache-samza/apache-kafka] Because RocksDB can write to disk, the maintained state can be larger than available main memory.
[src:apache-samza/apache-kafka] For fault-tolerance, all updates to local state stores are also written into a topic in the Kafka cluster.
[src:apache-samza/apache-kafka] This allows recreating state by reading those topics and feed all data into RocksDB.
[src:apache-samza/apache-samza] Samza allows users to build stateful applications that process data in real-time from multiple sources including Apache Kafka.
[src:apache-samza/apache-samza] Samza provides fault tolerance, isolation and stateful processing.
[src:apache-samza/apache-samza] Unlike batch systems such as Apache Hadoop or Apache Spark, it provides continuous computation and output, which result in sub-second response times.
[src:apache-samza/apache-samza] There are many players in the field of real-time stream processing and Samza is one of the mature products.
[src:apache-samza/apache-samza] The biggest installation is in LinkedIn.
[src:apache-samza/event-stream-processing] In computer science, **stream processing** (also known as **event stream processing**, **data stream processing**, or **distributed stream processing**) is a programming paradigm which views streams, or sequences of events in time, as the central input and output objects of computation.
[src:apache-samza/event-stream-processing] Stream processing encompasses dataflow programming, reactive programming, and distributed data processing.
[src:apache-samza/event-stream-processing] Stream processing systems use streaming algorithms to trace parallel processing for data streams.
[src:apache-samza/event-stream-processing] The stream processing paradigm simplifies parallel software and hardware by restricting the parallel computation that can be performed.
[src:apache-samza/event-stream-processing] Given a sequence of data (a *stream*), a series of operations (*kernel functions*) is applied to each element in the stream.
[src:apache-samza/event-stream-processing] Kernel functions are usually pipelined, and optimal local on-chip memory reuse is attempted, in order to minimize the loss in bandwidth, associated with external memory interaction.
[src:apache-samza/event-stream-processing] *Uniform streaming*, where one kernel function is applied to all elements in the stream, is typical.
[src:apache-samza/event-stream-processing] Since the kernel and stream abstractions expose data dependencies, compiler tools can fully automate and optimize on-chip management tasks.
[src:apache-samza/event-stream-processing] Stream processing hardware can use scoreboarding, for example, to initiate a direct memory access (DMA) when dependencies become known.
[src:apache-samza/event-stream-processing] The elimination of manual DMA management reduces software complexity, and an associated elimination for hardware cached I/O, reduces the data area expanse that has to be involved with service by specialized computational units such as arithmetic logic units.
[src:apache-samza/event-stream-processing] During the 1980s stream processing was explored within dataflow programming.
[src:apache-samza/event-stream-processing] An example is the language SISAL (Streams and Iteration in a Single Assignment Language).
[src:apache-samza/event-stream-processing] Stream processing is essentially a compromise, driven by a data-centric model that works very well for traditional DSP or GPU-type applications (such as image, video and digital signal processing) but less so for general purpose processing with more randomized data access (such as databases).
[src:apache-samza/event-stream-processing] By sacrificing some flexibility in the model, the implications allow easier, faster and more efficient execution.
[src:apache-samza/event-stream-processing] Depending on the context, processor design may be tuned for maximum efficiency or a trade-off for flexibility.
[src:apache-samza/event-stream-processing] For each record we can only read from the input, perform operations on it, and write to the output.
[src:apache-samza/event-stream-processing] It is permissible to have multiple inputs and multiple outputs, but never a piece of memory that is both readable and writable.
[src:apache-samza/event-stream-processing] By way of illustration, the following code fragments demonstrate detection of patterns within event streams.
[src:apache-samza/event-stream-processing] The first is an example of processing a data stream using a continuous SQL query (a query that executes forever processing arriving data based on timestamps and window duration).
[src:apache-samza/event-stream-processing] This code fragment illustrates a JOIN of two data streams, one for stock orders, and one for the resulting stock trades.
[src:apache-samza/event-stream-processing] The query outputs a stream of all Orders matched by a Trade within one second of the Order being placed.
[src:apache-samza/event-stream-processing] The output stream is sorted by timestamp, in this case, the timestamp from the Orders stream.
[src:apache-samza/event-stream-processing] Another sample code fragment detects weddings among a flow of external "events" such as church bells ringing, the appearance of a man in a tuxedo or morning suit, a woman in a flowing white gown and rice flying through the air.
[src:apache-samza/event-stream-processing] A "complex" or "composite" event is what one infers from the individual simple events: a wedding is happening.
[src:apache-samza/event-stream-processing] Basic computers started from a sequential execution paradigm.
[src:apache-samza/event-stream-processing] Traditional CPUs are SISD based, which means they conceptually perform only one operation at a time.
[src:apache-samza/event-stream-processing] As the computing needs of the world evolved, the amount of data to be managed increased very quickly.
[src:apache-samza/event-stream-processing] It was obvious that the sequential programming model could not cope with the increased need for processing power.
[src:apache-samza/event-stream-processing] Various efforts have been spent on finding alternative ways to perform massive amounts of computations but the only solution was to exploit some level of parallel execution.
[src:apache-samza/event-stream-processing] The result of those efforts was SIMD, a programming paradigm which allowed applying one instruction to multiple instances of (different) data.
[src:apache-samza/event-stream-processing] Most of the time, SIMD was being used in a SWAR environment.
[src:apache-samza/event-stream-processing] By using more complicated structures, one could also have MIMD parallelism.
[src:apache-samza/event-stream-processing] Although those two paradigms were efficient, real-world implementations were plagued with limitations from memory alignment problems to synchronization issues and limited parallelism.
[src:apache-samza/event-stream-processing] Only few SIMD processors survived as stand-alone components; most were embedded in standard CPUs.
[src:apache-samza/event-stream-processing] Consider a simple program adding up two arrays containing 100 4-component vectors (i.e.
