[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] The more complex the system, the more carefully all possible interactions have to be considered and prepared for.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] All implementations of RAID, redundant array of independent disks, except RAID 0, are examples of a fault-tolerant storage device that uses data redundancy.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] A lockstep fault-tolerant machine uses replicated elements operating in parallel.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] At any time, all the replications of each element should be in the same state.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] The same inputs are provided to each replication, and the same outputs are expected.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] The outputs of the replications are compared using a voting circuit.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] A machine with two replications of each element is termed dual modular redundant (DMR).
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] The voting circuit can then only detect a mismatch and recovery relies on other methods.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] A machine with three replications of each element is termed triple modular redundant (TMR).
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] The voting circuit can determine which replication is in error when a two-to-one vote is observed.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] In this case, the voting circuit can output the correct result, and discard the erroneous version.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] After this, the internal state of the erroneous replication is assumed to be different from that of the other two, and the voting circuit can switch to a DMR mode.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] This model can be applied to any larger number of replications.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] Lockstep fault-tolerant machines are most easily made fully synchronous, with each gate of each replication making the same state transition on the same edge of the clock, and the clocks to the replications being exactly in phase.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] However, it is possible to build lockstep systems without this requirement.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] Bringing the replications into synchrony requires making their internal stored states the same.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] They can be started from a fixed initial state, such as the reset state.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] Alternatively, the internal state of one replica can be copied to another replica.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] One variant of DMR is **pair-and-spare**.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] Two replicated elements operate in lockstep as a pair, with a voting circuit that detects any mismatch between their operations and outputs a signal indicating that there is an error.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] Another pair operates exactly the same way.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] A final circuit selects the output of the pair that does not proclaim that it is in error.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] Pair-and-spare requires four replicas rather than the three of TMR, but has been used commercially.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] The approach has performance costs: because the technique rewrites code to insert dynamic checks for address validity, execution time will increase by 80% to 500%.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] Recovery shepherding is a lightweight technique to enable software programs to recover from otherwise fatal errors such as null pointer dereference and divide by zero.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] Comparing to the failure oblivious computing technique, recovery shepherding works on the compiled program binary directly and does not need to recompile to program.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] It uses the just-in-time binary instrumentation framework Pin.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] It attaches to the application process when an error occurs, repairs the execution, tracks the repair effects as the execution continues, contains the repair effects within the application process, and detaches from the process after all repair effects are flushed from the process state.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] It does not interfere with the normal execution of the program and therefore incurs negligible overhead.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] For 17 of 18 systematically collected real world null-dereference and divide-by-zero errors, a prototype implementation enables the application to continue to execute to provide acceptable output and service to its users on the error-triggering inputs.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] The circuit breaker design pattern is a technique to avoid catastrophic failures in distributed systems.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] Redundancy is the provision of functional capabilities that would be unnecessary in a fault-free environment.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] This can consist of backup components that automatically "kick in" if one component fails.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] For example, large cargo trucks can lose a tire without any major consequences.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] They have many tires, and no one tire is critical (with the exception of the front tires, which are used to steer, but generally carry less load, each and in total, than the other four to 16, so are less likely to fail).
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] The idea of incorporating redundancy in order to improve the reliability of a system was pioneered by John von Neumann in the 1950s.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] Two kinds of redundancy are possible: space redundancy and time redundancy.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] Space redundancy provides additional components, functions, or data items that are unnecessary for fault-free operation.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] Space redundancy is further classified into hardware, software and information redundancy, depending on the type of redundant resources added to the system.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] In time redundancy the computation or data transmission is repeated and the result is compared to a stored copy of the previous result.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] The current terminology for this kind of testing is referred to as In Service Fault Tolerance Testing or ISFTT for short.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] There is a difference between fault tolerance and systems that rarely have problems.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] For instance, the Western Electric crossbar systems had failure rates of two hours per forty years, and therefore were highly *fault resistant*.
[src:apache-samza/fault-tolerance] But when a fault did occur, they stopped operating completely, and therefore were not *fault tolerant*.
